---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import PrivateHeader from "../../components/PrivateHeader.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

const roles = [
  {
    id: "ascend",
    company: "Ascend Wellness Holdings",
    title: "Senior EA to CEO & President",
    dates: "Jan 2025 - Jan 2026",
    industry: "Cannabis MSO (Multi-State Operator)",
    leaders: "Sam Brill (CEO), Frank Parullo (President)",
    context: `We started digging into this on our first call and got deep into the quarterly earnings overhaul. You described building a 5-6 week pre-earnings timeline from scratch, coordinating across IR, commercial (David Gacom), cultivation teams, and finance (Roman, Laura Warren). You introduced hard and soft deadlines because cannabis leadership "were not accustomed to being held accountable in that way." You managed 200+ stakeholders across 7 markets and handled board/committee/IR operations. We need to finish this deep-dive and cover the other major workstreams.`,
    questions: [
      {
        q: "Let's finish the earnings story. You described the before (no prep structure, last-minute materials, no ownership). Walk me through one specific earnings call from start to finish using your new system. What happened in week 1 vs. week 5? Who did what? What was the call itself like compared to before you built this?",
        why: "We need the full arc for a case study: broken state, your system, the result."
      },
      {
        q: "You mentioned screening public speaking consultants for the executives. Did Sam or Frank actually use one? What changed about their performance on earnings calls after your process was in place?",
        why: "Connecting your operational work to executive performance is powerful."
      },
      {
        q: "The 7-market coordination: which states were you covering? How did you manage communication across that many markets? Was there a system before you, or did you build it?",
        why: "Scale and geographic complexity are strong differentiators."
      },
      {
        q: "You were there during a period of M&A activity. What was your role in acquisitions? Were you managing due diligence logistics, coordinating between legal teams, handling confidential documents? Give me a specific deal or transaction you were involved in.",
        why: "M&A support at the EA level is rare and valuable."
      },
      {
        q: "Board and committee operations: how many board meetings per year? What did your prep process look like? How far in advance did you start? What was the quality of board materials before you vs. after?",
        why: "Board governance is a premium skill for fractional EA positioning."
      },
      {
        q: "You left Ascend voluntarily after a year. What was the honest reason? And when you left, what did the transition look like? Did they struggle to replace you? What broke when you were gone?",
        why: "What breaks when you leave is the strongest proof of your value."
      },
      {
        q: "Laura Warren (VP Finance) and Courtney (Director, now at Matteo) are both people you want recommendations from. What specifically would each of them say about working with you? What would they say you did that nobody else could?",
        why: "We'll use this language in testimonial drafts and case studies."
      },
      {
        q: "The 98% satisfaction rate across 200+ stakeholders: where does that number come from? Was there a formal survey? An internal review? Or is it your estimate? If it's an estimate, what's the real evidence that people were satisfied?",
        why: "We need to either cite the real source or find a more defensible way to state this."
      },
      {
        q: "What's one thing that went wrong at Ascend, something that didn't work the way you planned, and what did you do about it?",
        why: "Resilience stories are more compelling than perfection stories."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: "immunovant",
    company: "Immunovant",
    title: "Senior EA to CEO & General Counsel",
    dates: "Sep 2019 - Jul 2024",
    industry: "Clinical-Stage Biopharmaceutical",
    leaders: "CEO (name TBD), General Counsel, Pam Connelly (first CFO & CHRO), Renee (CFO), Pete Norini",
    context: `This is your longest tenure and your biggest growth story: nearly 5 years at a clinical-stage biopharma. You went from supporting the CEO to also supporting the General Counsel. You founded and led the Culture Committee (DEI workshops, wellness programs). You designed onboarding for 6 admin professionals with a 20% ramp-up reduction. Your resume claims a 30% improvement in decision-making effectiveness and 22% increase in employee satisfaction. Pam Connelly is someone you want a recommendation from. We have almost no specific stories from this role yet.`,
    questions: [
      {
        q: "Immunovant was a startup when you joined in 2019. How big was the company then vs. when you left in 2024? How many people? How many offices? What stage were they in clinically? Walk me through how your role changed as the company grew.",
        why: "Scaling with a startup is a compelling narrative arc."
      },
      {
        q: "You supported both the CEO and the General Counsel. How did that dual-support arrangement work? Did you manage competing priorities? Give me an example of a time their needs conflicted and how you handled it.",
        why: "Dual-exec support is a differentiator. We need a specific story."
      },
      {
        q: "The Culture Committee: whose idea was it? How did you pitch it? What specific programs did you create? How many people participated? What changed about the company culture that you can point to?",
        why: "Founding a culture initiative shows strategic leadership beyond the EA title."
      },
      {
        q: "You designed onboarding for 6 admin professionals and cut ramp-up time by 20%. What did onboarding look like before you? What did you build? How did you measure the 20% improvement? What specific materials or systems did you create?",
        why: "Building repeatable systems is exactly what fractional clients need."
      },
      {
        q: "The 30% improvement in decision-making effectiveness: I need to understand where this number comes from. What was happening before that was slowing decisions? What did you change? How was this measured or observed?",
        why: "This is a bold claim. We either need to back it up with a real story or reframe it."
      },
      {
        q: "The 22% employee satisfaction increase: same question. Was there an engagement survey? What was your specific contribution to that result?",
        why: "Same as above. Need the real source."
      },
      {
        q: "What would Pam Connelly say about you if I called her right now and asked, 'What's it like working with Leigh-Ann?' Give me her actual words, not a polished version.",
        why: "This becomes the testimonial draft."
      },
      {
        q: "You were there nearly 5 years. What's the biggest fire you put out that nobody knew about? The thing where if you hadn't stepped in, it would have been a disaster?",
        why: "The invisible saves are often the best case studies."
      },
      {
        q: "Clinical-stage biopharma has specific operational complexity: FDA timelines, clinical trial milestones, investor updates around data readouts. Were you involved in any of that? Did you coordinate logistics around major clinical announcements or FDA interactions?",
        why: "Industry-specific expertise is what commands premium rates."
      },
      {
        q: "Why did you leave after 5 years? What was the honest trigger? And what was the reaction when you gave notice?",
        why: "How hard it is to leave and how they react tells us your value."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: "third-bridge",
    company: "Third Bridge",
    title: "Senior EA to President, Global Lead & MD Operations",
    dates: "Oct 2017 - Sep 2019",
    industry: "Expert Network / Financial Services Research",
    leaders: "President (name TBD)",
    context: `Global role spanning NYC and London. You reduced event costs by 15%, expanded admin teams in both cities, and created onboarding manuals and how-to guides. This was your first role with international scope. We have very little detail beyond resume bullets.`,
    questions: [
      {
        q: "Third Bridge is an expert network connecting investors with industry specialists. How did that business model affect your day-to-day? Were you coordinating with clients (hedge funds, PE firms) directly, or was your scope internal?",
        why: "Understanding the business context makes the case study richer."
      },
      {
        q: "You supported the President of a company with offices in NYC and London. How did you manage the time zone gap? What did a typical day look like when you were coordinating across both offices?",
        why: "Global coordination is a premium skill."
      },
      {
        q: "The 15% cost reduction on events: which events? How many per year? What was the total budget you were managing? What specifically did you change to cut costs, and was quality maintained?",
        why: "We need the real numbers behind the percentage."
      },
      {
        q: "You expanded the admin teams in NYC and London. How many people did you hire? Did you build the job descriptions, run the interviews, make the hiring decisions? What was the team size before vs. after?",
        why: "Team building is a Chief of Staff function, not an EA function. This elevates your positioning."
      },
      {
        q: "The onboarding manuals and how-to guides you created: are these still in use? How many did you write? What problems were they solving? Were new admins getting up to speed faster because of them?",
        why: "Creating institutional knowledge that outlasts you is a strong proof point."
      },
      {
        q: "What was the biggest difference between working at Third Bridge vs. PwC? What did the jump from Big Four to a smaller, global company teach you?",
        why: "Career progression narrative."
      },
      {
        q: "If I asked the President you supported to describe your impact in one sentence, what would they say?",
        why: "Testimonial language."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: "pwc",
    company: "PwC",
    title: "Senior Team Assistant, NY Metro State & Local Tax",
    dates: "Nov 2012 - Jun 2017",
    industry: "Big Four Professional Services",
    leaders: "Tax partners (names TBD)",
    context: `Nearly 5 years at PwC supporting the State & Local Tax practice in the NY Metro office. You achieved 98% on-time delivery, managed Fortune 500 workflows, tracked the Marketing & Sales budget, and served as a mentor and onboarding buddy. This is a strong brand name on the resume but we have almost no stories.`,
    questions: [
      {
        q: "PwC's State & Local Tax practice: how many partners and senior managers were you supporting? What was the team size? Were you the only assistant, or part of an admin team?",
        why: "Scale and ratio matter. Supporting 1 partner vs. 8 is a different story."
      },
      {
        q: "Fortune 500 workflows: what does that actually mean in your day-to-day? Were you handling engagement letters, client billing, audit support materials? Give me a specific example of a complex workflow you managed.",
        why: "The resume bullet is vague. We need the real story."
      },
      {
        q: "The Marketing & Sales budget tracking: how large was this budget? What system did you use? What happened before you took it over? Were there errors or gaps you found and fixed?",
        why: "Budget ownership is an operations skill, not an admin skill."
      },
      {
        q: "You were a mentor and onboarding buddy. How many people did you onboard? What did that look like? Did you create any materials, or was it informal? Did PwC have a formal program, or did you volunteer for this?",
        why: "Mentorship shows leadership and institutional investment."
      },
      {
        q: "Tax season at a Big Four firm is intense. What was your role during peak season (Jan-Apr)? How did the workload change? What did you handle that nobody else could?",
        why: "High-pressure, deadline-driven environments are exactly what C-suite executives need from an EA."
      },
      {
        q: "You were at PwC for nearly 5 years. That's long for an assistant role at a Big Four. What kept you there? And what finally made you leave for Third Bridge?",
        why: "Career transition narrative."
      },
      {
        q: "Is there anyone from PwC who would still vouch for you today? A partner, a senior manager, a fellow assistant?",
        why: "Long-tenure references from brand-name firms carry weight."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: "reich-tang",
    company: "Reich & Tang",
    title: "Operations EA to VP & COO",
    dates: "Feb 2010 - Sep 2012",
    industry: "Financial Services / Asset Management",
    leaders: "VP & COO (name TBD)",
    context: `You supported the VP & COO at a financial services firm. You created procedure manuals, improved accuracy by 20%, reduced training time by 30%, and distributed reports to 100+ brokers. This overlaps with your time at DGB Management.`,
    questions: [
      {
        q: "Reich & Tang was a deposit management and asset servicing firm. What was the COO responsible for, and where did you fit into that? Were you managing operations-level tasks, or was this traditional EA work?",
        why: "Understanding the scope tells us if this was admin or operations leadership."
      },
      {
        q: "The procedure manuals you created: how many? For what processes? Were these replacing tribal knowledge (people just knew how to do things) with documented systems? Are they still in use?",
        why: "Codifying institutional knowledge is a fractional CoS skill."
      },
      {
        q: "Report distribution to 100+ brokers: was this a daily thing? Weekly? What was in these reports? What happened if they were late or wrong? What was the consequence of an error?",
        why: "Stakes and volume tell the real story."
      },
      {
        q: "The 20% accuracy improvement and 30% training time reduction: where do these numbers come from? What was inaccurate before? What was taking so long in training?",
        why: "We need the real before/after."
      },
      {
        q: "You were at Reich & Tang and DGB Management at the same time. How did you balance two roles? Was DGB a side business?",
        why: "Understanding the overlap and entrepreneurial drive."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: "dgb",
    company: "DGB Management",
    title: "Virtual Operations Consultant",
    dates: "Aug 2009 - Dec 2011",
    industry: "Independent Consulting",
    leaders: "Your own business",
    context: `This was your first independent consulting work, running your own virtual operations practice. You achieved a 30% reduction in routine process time for clients. We know almost nothing about this.`,
    questions: [
      {
        q: "DGB Management: what does DGB stand for? Was this a registered business? How did you get your first client?",
        why: "The origin story of your consulting practice matters for your fractional positioning today."
      },
      {
        q: "Who were your clients? How many at any given time? What industries? What size companies?",
        why: "Your fractional EA pitch today has roots here. We need to connect the dots."
      },
      {
        q: "What services did you actually provide? Calendar management? Process design? Financial operations? Give me a specific project that went well.",
        why: "One good project becomes a case study."
      },
      {
        q: "The 30% reduction in routine process time: for which client? What process? How did you measure it?",
        why: "A specific example is more compelling than a blanket claim."
      },
      {
        q: "Why did you stop? You went from running your own thing to going back to a full-time role at PwC. What drove that decision?",
        why: "This is relevant to your fractional pivot today. Different stage of life, different leverage."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: "bearingpoint",
    company: "BearingPoint",
    title: "Financial Operations Administrator",
    dates: "Dec 2007 - Jul 2009",
    industry: "Management & Technology Consulting",
    leaders: "Manager/Director (name TBD)",
    context: `Your first major US corporate role after arriving from Trinidad. You processed $10M+ in monthly payments with 99% accuracy and reduced billing discrepancies by 20%. BearingPoint was a major consulting firm that went bankrupt in 2009.`,
    questions: [
      {
        q: "You were processing $10M+ in monthly payments. Walk me through what that actually looked like day to day. What systems were you using? How many invoices or transactions per month? What happened if something was wrong?",
        why: "The volume and stakes behind '$10M+' need to be real and specific."
      },
      {
        q: "BearingPoint filed for bankruptcy in February 2009 and you left in July 2009. What was it like working through the collapse of a major consulting firm? What did you handle during that period that was beyond your normal scope?",
        why: "Crisis resilience is a compelling story, especially for your first US corporate role."
      },
      {
        q: "The 20% reduction in billing discrepancies: what was causing the discrepancies? What did you change? Was this a process you fixed, a tool you built, or something else?",
        why: "The fix is more interesting than the percentage."
      },
      {
        q: "This was your first corporate role in the US after moving from Trinidad. What was the biggest adjustment? What surprised you? What skills from Petrotrin transferred directly?",
        why: "Immigration + career story is part of your brand narrative."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: "petrotrin",
    company: "Petrotrin (Petroleum Company of Trinidad and Tobago)",
    title: "Administrative Assistant, Office of the VP of Oil & Refining",
    dates: "Pre-2006",
    industry: "State-Owned Oil & Gas",
    leaders: "VP of Oil & Refining (name TBD)",
    context: `Your origin story. Petrotrin was Trinidad's state-owned oil company (merged from Trintoc and Trinmar). You worked in the office of the VP of Oil & Refining before moving to the US. We know almost nothing about this role.`,
    questions: [
      {
        q: "Petrotrin was one of the biggest employers in Trinidad. How old were you when you started? How did you get the job? Was this your first real office job?",
        why: "Origin story. Where the work ethic was forged."
      },
      {
        q: "The VP of Oil & Refining: what was this person responsible for? How big was their team? What was your scope?",
        why: "Supporting a VP at a national oil company is a bigger deal than people might assume."
      },
      {
        q: "What was the work culture like? What did you learn at Petrotrin that you still carry with you today?",
        why: "Formative professional experiences anchor the career narrative."
      },
      {
        q: "What made you decide to leave Trinidad and move to the US? Was there a specific moment or was it gradual?",
        why: "The immigration decision is the hinge point of your entire career story."
      },
      {
        q: "When you arrived in the US in 2006, what happened between then and starting at BearingPoint in late 2007? That's roughly 18 months. What were you doing?",
        why: "Filling the gap and understanding the transition."
      }
    ]
  }
];
---

<Layout noindex={true} title="Case Study Deep-Dive Questions | Leigh-Ann Martin" description="Role-by-role questions to extract metrics, impact, and stories for case studies.">
  <PrivateHeader />
  <div class="md:ml-60">
  <main>
    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="bg-primary pt-24 pb-12 md:pt-16 md:pb-16">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 text-center">
        <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-secondary mb-4">Session 2 Prep</p>
        <h1 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl text-white leading-tight mb-4">
          Case Study Deep-Dive Questions
        </h1>
        <p class="text-white/50 text-base leading-relaxed max-w-xl mx-auto mb-6">
          Role-by-role questions designed to uncover the real metrics, stories, and impact behind your career. The goal is to build case studies with specifics that make hiring managers and prospects say "I need that person."
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-2">
          <span class="bg-white/10 border border-white/10 text-white/60 text-xs px-3 py-1 rounded-full">8 Roles</span>
          <span class="bg-white/10 border border-white/10 text-white/60 text-xs px-3 py-1 rounded-full">65+ Questions</span>
          <span class="bg-white/10 border border-white/10 text-white/60 text-xs px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Metrics &amp; Impact</span>
          <span class="bg-white/10 border border-white/10 text-white/60 text-xs px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Testimonial Language</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Quick Nav -->
    <section class="bg-primary/95 border-t border-white/[0.06] py-4 sticky top-14 md:top-0 z-40">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-2 text-xs">
          <a href="#how-to-use" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">How to Use</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#quantification" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">Quantification</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#calculators" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">Calculators</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          {roles.map((role, i) => (
            <>
              <a href={`#${role.id}`} class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">{role.company.split(' ')[0]}{role.company === "Petrotrin (Petroleum Company of Trinidad and Tobago)" ? "" : ""}</a>
              {i < roles.length - 1 && <span class="text-white/15">|</span>}
            </>
          ))}
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#cross-cutting" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">Cross-Cutting</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- How to Use -->
    <section id="how-to-use" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl text-primary mb-6">How to Use This</h2>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6 space-y-4">
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-secondary font-bold text-sm mt-0.5">1.</span>
            <div><span class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm">Go role by role.</span> <span class="text-text-muted text-sm">Start with the most recent (Ascend) and work backwards. The newer roles need the most depth. The older ones need the stories you haven't told yet.</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-secondary font-bold text-sm mt-0.5">2.</span>
            <div><span class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm">Use Otter or voice notes.</span> <span class="text-text-muted text-sm">Don't type these out. Open Otter (or your phone's voice recorder) and talk through the answers out loud. Talking pulls out details that writing filters out.</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-secondary font-bold text-sm mt-0.5">3.</span>
            <div><span class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm">Be specific, not polished.</span> <span class="text-text-muted text-sm">We're not looking for perfect answers. We want real numbers, real names, real situations. "I think it was about 15 invoices a day" is more useful than "I managed high-volume payment processing."</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-secondary font-bold text-sm mt-0.5">4.</span>
            <div><span class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm">The "what we know" boxes show your starting point.</span> <span class="text-text-muted text-sm">Each role starts with a summary of what we already have from your resume, our call, and your proposal. Read it, then go deeper.</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-secondary font-bold text-sm mt-0.5">5.</span>
            <div><span class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm">Skip what doesn't apply.</span> <span class="text-text-muted text-sm">Not every question will land. If one doesn't fit, move on. But if a question triggers a memory or a story, follow that thread.</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Quantification Playbook -->
    <section id="quantification" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-warm">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Before You Start</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-3">How to Turn Fuzzy Achievements Into Hard Numbers</h2>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-8">Most people undersell their impact because they think they need exact data. You don't. You need defensible estimates. Here are six frameworks to quantify work that feels hard to measure.</p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
          <!-- Framework 1 -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-5">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <div class="w-8 h-8 bg-secondary/10 rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
                <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-secondary" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 8v4l3 3m6-3a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"/></svg>
              </div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm">Time Saved = Money Saved</h3>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs leading-relaxed mb-2">If you saved your CEO 5 hours a week, and they earn $500K, that's $120K/year in recovered executive time. The formula:</p>
            <div class="bg-cream rounded-lg px-3 py-2 text-xs font-mono text-primary">(hours saved/week) x 52 x (exec annual comp / 2,080) = annual value</div>
          </div>

          <!-- Framework 2 -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-5">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <div class="w-8 h-8 bg-secondary/10 rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
                <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-secondary" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m5.618-4.016A11.955 11.955 0 0112 2.944a11.955 11.955 0 01-8.618 3.04A12.02 12.02 0 003 9c0 5.591 3.824 10.29 9 11.622 5.176-1.332 9-6.03 9-11.622 0-1.042-.133-2.052-.382-3.016z"/></svg>
              </div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm">Error Prevention = Risk Avoided</h3>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs leading-relaxed mb-2">Processing $10M/month at 99% vs. 95% accuracy? That's $4.8M in prevented errors per year. Even small accuracy gains are massive at volume.</p>
            <div class="bg-cream rounded-lg px-3 py-2 text-xs font-mono text-primary">(volume) x (old error rate - new error rate) x (avg transaction) = risk avoided</div>
          </div>

          <!-- Framework 3 -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-5">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <div class="w-8 h-8 bg-secondary/10 rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
                <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-secondary" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M17 20h5v-2a3 3 0 00-5.356-1.857M17 20H7m10 0v-2c0-.656-.126-1.283-.356-1.857M7 20H2v-2a3 3 0 015.356-1.857M7 20v-2c0-.656.126-1.283.356-1.857m0 0a5.002 5.002 0 019.288 0M15 7a3 3 0 11-6 0 3 3 0 016 0z"/></svg>
              </div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm">Stakeholder Scale = Complexity Managed</h3>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs leading-relaxed mb-2">200+ stakeholders across 7 markets isn't just a number. It's thousands of touchpoints per year. Each one is a potential miscommunication you prevented.</p>
